1 Introduction

This vignette will demonstrate a full T cell trajectory inference workflow, including preprocessing,clonotype-level trajectory estimation, trajectory clustering,pseudotime estimation and trajectory cluster marker prediction.

2 Dataset

We will demonstrate the usage of LRT via a real dataset from Khatun et al.This dataset consists of scTCR-seq data and scRNA-seq data from five mice. The raw data can be accessed at https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE158896.

3 Load packages

## load LRT package
library(LRT)

The LRT package has multiple dependencies, to use it smoothly, it is advised to install the dependencies before using LRT.

## load dependencies

packages <- c("Seurat", "dplyr", "tibble","dtwclust", "progress", "DT", "shiny", "shinyBS","ggplot2",'sbm','pheatmap')

# Install packages not yet installed
installed_packages <- packages %in% rownames(installed.packages())
if (any(installed_packages == FALSE)) {
  install.packages(packages[!installed_packages])
}
# Packages loading
invisible(lapply(packages, library, character.only = TRUE))

if (!require("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE))
    install.packages("BiocManager")

BiocManager::install("slingshot","SingleCellExperiment","tradeSeq")

4 Data preprocessing

To begin our analysis of the clonotye lineage, we need to prepare a dataframe containing clonotype information and a seurat object containing cell id, UMAP coordinates and clustering labels.

An example R code is provided at https://github.com/JuanXie19/LRT/blob/master/preprocess.r, which illustrates the data pre-processing step and prepares the input for our analysis.

5 Combine scTCR-seq and scRNA-seq data

After pre-processing, we need to attach the clonotype information from scTCR-seq to the seurat object.

For the clonotype information,you can choose anything you like, as long as it can be used to define clonotype. Common choices are CDR3 amino acid/nucleotide sequence (either \(\alpha\) chain, \(\beta\) chain or paired \(\alpha \beta\) chain). Note that the clonotype information must be saved in a column named cdr3 in the scTCR-seq data. An example pre-processed seurat object is provided at https://drive.google.com/file/d/17r8WkAIyLmGwaEP4wLHnQkF2nvWDXUPd/view?usp=sharing, and example scTCR-seq data is provided at https://drive.google.com/file/d/1P80GIvhpcZS6ss3m-gf4MwYFJw8UQiKg/view?usp=sharing. Users can download these example data and explore the functions.

To combine scTCR-seq and scRNA-seq data, users can simply call the getCombinedDataSet function.

# load TCR data
TCR <-read.csv('/path/to/scTCR-seqData/TCR.csv') 

# load seurat object with clustering labels and UMAP coordinates
load('Mice.sub2.rda') 

# combine TCR and scRNA-seq
Combined <- getCombinedDataSet(TCR, Mice.sub2)

The combined dataset is an updated Seurat object. Users could directly access the object via @seurat. They can also easily access the components (seurat cluster labels and TCR sequences) by calling the corresponding accessor functions:

# have a look at the combined dataset
Combined

6 Exploratory analysis of clonotypes

After combining the data, users can conduct exploratory analysis of the clonotypes by calling shinyClone function.

The shinyClone will trigger a Shiny app, which consists of two tabs, Clonotype and Repertoire. Clonotype shows a table of clonotype, along with the relevant information, e.g., how many cells are associated with each clonotype and how these cells are distributed among cell clusters. If the user clicks a clonotype in this table, they can also check the distribution of cells associated with each clonotype on the UMAP plot. The plot can also be downloaded by clicking the button below the plot.A cell density plot is also displayed for clones spanning more than 10 cells.


# explore the distribution of clonotypes
shinyClone(Combined)

The Repertoire tab provides commonly used repertoire analysis functionalities, including clonal diversity, clonal homeostasis, clonal proportion, and clonal overlap analyses.

The Repertoire tab in shinyClone

7 T cell trajectory inference

The T cell trajectory inference consists of three steps, clonotype-level trajectory inference, trajectory clustering, pseudotime estimation and trajectory cluster marker identification.

7.1 Clonotype-level trajectory inference

Users can infer clonotype-level trajectories using the getClonotypeLineages function. Users can control the ways that the trajectories are inferred (for details, please refer to the function documentation). One thing to note is that it is advised to specify the root of the lineage, as the order of lineage is very important for the later lineage clustering step.

The inferred lineages can be accessed via calling the lrtLineages function. Users can also take a look at the parameters via calling lrtParams function.

load('C:/project/TCR-seq/Gang/GSE158896_RAW/trajectory0801.rda')
# infer lineages. Here use Tcmp as the root
Trajectory <- getClonotypeLineages(Combined,start.clus = 'Tcmp', end.clus = NULL, dist.method = 'simple', use.median = TRUE)

# Access one of the inferred lineages
lrtLineages(Trajectory)[[1]]

# Access the parameters
lrtParams(Trajectory)

7.2 Trajectory clustering

It is noted that some lineages are grouped together, indicating that some clonotypes may share similar trajectory. To find such groups, users could apply shinyClust function to conduct clustering analysis.



# clust the lineages
shinyClust(Trajectory,Combined)

The shinyClust will trigger another Shiny app that allows users to intuitively and dynamically conduct clustering analysis of clonotype-level trajectory. Whenever usres specify the desired number of clusters, shinyClust automatically update clustering results. shinyClust consists of three tabs, Clustering exploration, Trajectory clustering and DE analysis.

The Clustering exploration tab allows users to implement trajectory clustering in an interactive manner. While SBM is set to be a default here, other clustering algorithms are provided for flexibility, including hierarchical and partitional clustering. Users can also tune parameters for each clustering algorithm. This page will show either ICL or silhouette scores under the current setting, to assist users to evaluate and determine the optimal number of clusters.

Clustering exploration tab

On the Trajectory clustering tab, upon choosing a particular cluster to display, shinyClust updates (i) a trajectory plot, which shows clonotype trajectories corresponding to the trajectory cluster on the UMAP plot, and (ii) a cell distribution plot, which shows the cells associated with this trajectory cluster on the UMAP plot.

Trajectory clustering tab

7.3 Trajectory cluster marker prediction

Finally, in the DE analysis tab of the shinyClust, users can implement DE analysis, which fits the NB-GAM model and conducts Wald test in the backend using the R package tradeSeq. Here shinyClust shows a table of predicted DE genes with both raw and Bonferroni-adjusted p-values, as well as a heatmap of DE gene expression values. If users are interested in how the expression values of a particular gene vary along pseudotime, they can click the row in the table and the page will show a scatter plot of log read count versus pseudotime, along with the fitted smoothing spline.

DE analysis tab
